  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">28</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">Here we have used Eq. 6.1.15 of [17]</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">29</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">Here we have used the relation -1 = e-iπ(1+2n), where the resonance parameter n is an integer</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">30</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">Taking cognizance of the relation (20) and using Eq. 6.1.23 of [17], one deduces that the ratio Γ(ν)/Γ(-ν) is a complex number of the form eiφ, where φ ∈ implies [Γ(ν)/Γ(-ν)]1/2i|ν| ∈ R. One therefore concludes that, for imaginary values of the dimensionless parameter ν [see Eqs. (11) and (20)], the dimensionless radii µR(n) of the charged supporting shells as obtained from the analytically derived formula (27) are purely real numbers</subfield>
    <subfield code="h">R. This</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">31</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">Note that µR &lt; |ν| [see Eqs. (11) and (19)], which implies x &lt; 1 (or equivalently, ǫ &gt; 0)</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">32</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">Here we have used the relation -i = e-iπ( 1 2 +2n), where the resonance parameter n is an integer</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">33</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">Interestingly, from the data presented in Table II one finds that the agreement between the numerical data [as obtained from a direct numerical solution of the resonance equation (15)] and the analytical formula (27) is quite good even in the regime µR = O(1). This finding is quite surprising since the analytically derived formula (27) for the discrete spectrum of charged shell radii which can support the static bound-state charged massive scalar field configurations is formally valid in the restricted regime µR ≪ 1 [see Eqs. (22) and (25)]</subfield>
